observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to direct the MAO to:
Make the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the accurate balances of the AP and other affected accounts;
Ensure that the effects of MGJ’s financial transactions are faithfully and accurately represented in the FS in compliance with IPSAS 1;
Adhere strictly to the criteria provided by COA Circular No. 2015-009 and use the appropriate account titles when recording the Municipality’s financial transactions; and
Review the items in the AP accounts with no details as to their nature to properly account them in the FS.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Prioritize filling vacant plantilla positions and, when necessary, utilize casual or emergency staff hiring practices in accordance with CSC guidelines and other relevant rule and regulations;
Undertake a comprehensive study and analysis of the Municipality’s staffing pattern to develop a reliable HRP. Furthermore, strictly implementation of EO No. 39s series of 2023, or the internal policy for hiring JO/COS in the Municipality to provide clear guidelines and controls over the hiring of JO/COS personnel;
Review the existing LGU policy on hiring JO personnel with particular focus on the possibilities that hiring such services does not rest solely in the recommendations of the agency head but also with the direct participation of the MHRMO for better system of check and balances; and
Require the MA and MHRMO to include the department head’s certification for offsetting days as part of the documentary requirements for claims by the JO personnel to avoid any suspension in audit.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to:
Require the MA and MGSO, with the assistance from the Municipal Engineering Office, to continue exerting effort in locating the details of the beginning balances and update their respective books and records;
Require the MA to continue evaluating thoroughly PPE acquired in current and prior years which were given to other agencies and draw appropriate journal entries to adjust/correct all noted deficiencies for accurate and fair presentation of the PPE accounts;
Require the MA and MGSO to: (i) reconcile the accounting and property records, and investigate and institute appropriate action for any deficiency noted; and (ii) maintain properly the required accounting and property records; and
Assign temporarily to other personnel some workloads of the members of the Inventory Committee Team during the conduct of physical count as required under Section 5.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require the MA to verify meticulously the status of long outstanding fund transfers/payables still maintained in the books and adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 111 of PD No. 1445;
Implement the programs which are already approved and request the Sangguniang Bayan to pass a resolution authorizing the use of excess fund counterpart;
Require the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to confirm the payables from the SAs to verify their existence and if validated, remit immediately to the SAs the unutilized balances pursuant to existing contracts; and
Remit to the Bureau of Treasury in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-001, the cash backup of fund transfers, the nature and SAs of which could no longer be identified for lack of information.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the JWS Administrator to come up with other strategies to improve further the income generation.  Specifically, we suggested the following measures:
Intensify the collection of JWS concessionaires fee through strict implementation of rules and procedures;
Conduct a comprehensive study on the operation to identify weaknesses in the collection system and device strategies to encourage consumer to pay concessionaires fees to increase income;
Avoid overstaffing, but rather maximize efficiently the work of personnel involved in the operation of JWS;
Evaluate expenses for Water, Electricity, Supplies, Repairs and Maintenance and implement economy measures to reduce losses in operation.  Also, check regularly systems loss brought about by leaking transmission lines; and
Trim down the operational expenditures and promote efficiency among workers;
Likewise, we recommended and the LCE agreed to require the MA to:
Prepare separate financial reports for JWS operation to provide adequate information on the results of operation for monitoring and decision-making purposes; and
Recognize the balance of uncollected concessionaire’s fee as receivables and revenue at the end of each year.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Increase the bonding requirements of the DO pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 to protect the interest of the Municipality, otherwise ensure that the CA granted is within the limit of her fidelity bond;
Require the concerned DO to settle immediately her outstanding CAs due for liquidation by demanding the submission of liquidation reports and supporting documents. Otherwise, cause the withholding or suspension of their salaries for non-compliance therewith;
Strengthen control measures to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of CAs by monitoring strictly the period of liquidation and impose sanctions on AO who failed to liquidate on time; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the:
Municipal Engineer to conduct an inventory of project accomplishments and furnish the Statement of Work Accomplishments to the MA;
MA to impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one per cent (0.1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion of the works for every day of delay;
Contractor to engage the catch-up program in order to fast tract the completion of the project to avoid termination of contract as stipulated in Annex I of the Revised IRR 2016 of R.A. No. 9184;
Intensify project monitoring to avoid recurrence of delay in completion/implementation; and
Adhere strictly to the regulation on posting of project billboard for future projects immediately after the award of contract for transparency purposes.

We recommended that Management:

Require the MGSO and the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;


Direct the Municipal Accountant to exhaust all efforts to fully identify the PPE with lump sum balances and at the same time secure the documents to reconcile them with the Inventory Report of the MGSO;

Require the MGSO to conduct physical inventory and inspection of all unserviceable and obsolete items so that they may be properly disposed of and dropped from the books of accounts in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006; 

Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Accounting Office concerned personnel trace back prior years’ acquisitions to have complete details of the PPE accounts that will serve as basis in the computation of depreciation, in order to present true value of the depreciable PPE in the FS.

Reconcile thoroughly the Cash in Bank accounts in order to come up with the correct balances of the said accounts presented in the FS;

Ensure that all valid reconciling items to be recorded and adjusted in the books are properly supported with complete documents; and 

Exercise due diligence and professional care in the conduct of reconciliation of records and in the performance of functions especially in the recording of journal entries and mathematical computation thereof.

We recommended that Management:

Include in the appropriations the titling of the land owned by the Municipality;

Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority to confirm the ownership of all land properties and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto;

Ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to record the properties over which the Municipality has acquired absolute ownership.

We recommended that Management:

Enjoin the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office (LDRRMO) to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;

Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRM Fund to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization.

Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation, impart the benefits of paying early and/or on time and consider condonation of fines and penalties to delinquent tax payers;

Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; and

Post the notice of delinquency in the payment of RPT in the main entrance of the municipal building and other conspicuous public places frequently visited by people.

