Direct the LDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMF Investment Plan detailing all the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the unutilized balance of CY 2014 amounting to ₱107,037.03 from Special Trust Fund to General Fund for other social services as prescribed in Section 21 of RA No. 10121; and

Advice the Municipal DRRM Council to prioritize the utilization of the unexpended balance of LDRRM Fund for CY 2015 to ensure that this fund is used for the intended purpose within the prescribed period.

We recommended that Management:

Require the concerned personnel to secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document of all land properties registered under the name of the Municipality from the Land Registration Authority (LRA) and ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles; 

Thereafter, require the Municipal Accountant to record the properties over which the Municipality has acquired absolute ownership.

We recommended that Management facilitate the immediate disposal of the aforementioned unserviceable properties to recoup any salvage value thereof. Specifically, we recommended the following measures:

Conduct physical inspection and appraisal of the unserviceable properties and waste materials and furnish the auditor copies of fully accomplished/verified Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties;
Dispose the unserviceable properties based on the most appropriate mode of disposal pursuant to the provisions of COA Circular No. 92-386.

Require the MGSO and the Municipal Accounting Office to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the MGSO to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes; and
Require the MGSO to conduct physical inventory and inspection of all unserviceable and obsolete items so that they may be properly disposed of and dropped from the books of accounts in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular Nos. 89-296 and 92-386.

Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Direct the LDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the unutilized balance of CY 2014 amounting to ₱107,037.03 from STF to GF for other social services as prescribed in Section 21 of RA No. 10121; and
Advice the MDRRMC to prioritize the utilization of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF for CY 2015 to ensure that this fund is used for the intended purpose within the prescribed period.

Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation, impart the benefits of paying early and/or on time and consider condonation of fines and penalties to delinquent tax payers;
Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; and
Post the notice of delinquency in the payment of RPT in the main entrance of the municipal building and other conspicuous public places frequently visited by people.

Expedite the submission of the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction; and
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
We also recommended that Management encourage the remaining five barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that Management:

Follow up the approval of the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction; 

Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation; 

Exert continuous effort in educating the people of Juban the importance of solid waste management.

We recommended that Management facilitate the immediate disposal of the aforementioned unserviceable properties to recoup any salvage value thereof. Specifically, we recommended the following measures:
Conduct physical inspection and appraisal of the unserviceable properties and waste materials and furnish the auditor copies of fully accomplished/verified IIRUPs;
Dispose the unserviceable properties based on the most appropriate mode of disposal pursuant to the provisions of COA Circular No. 92-386.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that Management:
Follow up the approval of the 10-year Municipal Solid Waste Management Plan to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize solid waste management programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Exert continuous effort in educating the people of Juban the importance of solid waste management.
